The idea is to model each component with a different model. The trend and the seasonal component models are automatically created by the function seasonal_decompose, so we can focus on the noise part.

Using auto-correlation and partial auto-correlation plots we can try to understand which model to use.

Autocorrelation drops slowly while partial autocorrelation has only 1 significant value at lag 1. So we can try using an AR(1) model. If the plots where inverted, an MA(1) might have been the correct choice.

First we create a lagged version of the response variable.

In [248]:
decomposition["lag_TotPassengerCount_epsilon"] = st.lag(decomposition["TotPassengerCount_epsilon"], 1)._over(
                                                                    order_by = [decomposition["DtActivityPeriod"]])

Then we can use a linear regression to implement an AR(1)

In [214]:
from verticapy.learn.linear_model import LinearRegression
model = LinearRegression(name = "LR_airpassenger_noise")

model.drop()
model.fit(decomposition, ["lag_TotPassengerCount_epsilon"], "TotPassengerCount_epsilon")

For the first part of the test dataset, our model works great.

But from March, the covid shock makes our model overestimate the values.

We can plot the residuals to try to understand the pattern in the shock

In [228]:
test_j.hchart(x = "DtActivityPeriod",
                     y = ["res"],
                     kind = "line")
Out[228]:

The shock seems to be composed of two different parts.

  • the first two periods (march and april) have a stronger component of shock (because of the total lockdown imposed)
  • starting from may, the shock is less pronounced, and equally affect all the periods after

We can create dummy variables which are always zeroes except for the interested periods, multiply by the effect and substract them from our prediction.
